The paper proposes new coverage queries for trajectory databases and focuses on efficient query processing using a novel index structure. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.DB (databases) sub-category. Additionally, the paper proposes algorithms that utilize divide-and-conquer and best-first strategies, which are commonly used in the cs.AI (artificial intelligence) and cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) sub-categories. The paper also discusses the use of quadtree and z-ordering, which are relevant to the cs.GR (graphics) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates its algorithms through an extensive experimental study, which is relevant to the cs.SI (social and information networks) sub-category.
